6 AS INTRODUCED
7 An Act relating to torts; defining term; creating
limitation of action for body dysmorphia affirmation
8 procedures; providing for codification; and providing
an effective date.
9
10
11 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
12 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
13 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 18A of Title 76, unless there is
14 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
15 A. As used in this section:
16 1. "Anorexia affirmation procedures" means the following
17 medical or surgical services performed for the purpose of attempting
18 to affirm the perception of a person diagnosed with anorexia nervosa
19 about his or her body weight, if that perception is inconsistent
20 with the actual, current body weight of the person:
21 a. surgical procedures intended to result in weight loss,
22 also known as bariatric surgeries, or
23 b. weight-loss drugs, or other drugs to suppress hunger
24 or appetite;
Req. No. 10516 Page 1

1 2. a. "BIID affirmation procedures" means medical or
2 surgical services performed for the purpose of
3 attempting to affirm the perception of a person
4 diagnosed with Body Integrity Identity Disorder about
5 his or her body, if that perception is inconsistent
6 with the actual, current physique of the person.
7 b. BIID affirmation procedures include surgical
8 procedures that amputate or remove healthy body parts
9 without a clear physical and medical need including,
10 but not limited to, leg, arm, finger, toe, eye, ear,
11 tongue, lip, or nose;
12 3. a. "Gender transition procedures" means the following
13 medical or surgical services performed for the purpose
14 of attempting to affirm the person's perception of his
15 or her gender or biological sex, if that perception is
16 inconsistent with the person's biological sex:
17 (1) surgical procedures that alter or remove physical
18 or anatomical characteristics or features that
19 are typical for the individual’s biological sex,
20 or
21 (2) puberty-blocking drugs, cross-sex hormones, or
22 other drugs to suppress or delay normal puberty
23 or to promote the development of feminizing or
24
